00:49:52.120 --> 00:49:53.640
No, three.


00:49:53.640 --> 00:49:56.520
We've got the website, of course,


00:49:56.520 --> 00:50:01.000
and some microservices that interact with the website.


00:50:01.000 --> 00:50:02.600
Snackbox is an interesting one.


00:50:02.600 --> 00:50:07.240
That's a completely sandboxed Python evaluation tool.


00:50:07.240 --> 00:50:08.400
That's right, yeah.


00:50:08.400 --> 00:50:11.720
So that we can have a command on the server


00:50:11.720 --> 00:50:16.200
where people can run actual raw Python code without them


00:50:16.200 --> 00:50:18.640
being able to destroy all our servers.


00:50:18.640 --> 00:50:21.240
Because there is, of course, a risk associated with people--


00:50:21.240 --> 00:50:23.280
Yeah, that's the danger of it.


00:50:23.280 --> 00:50:24.520
You want to test this code out?


00:50:24.520 --> 00:50:25.080
Click here.


00:50:25.080 --> 00:50:26.640
Oh, wait, the code I'm trying to test


00:50:26.640 --> 00:50:32.000
is subprocess launch such and such, or whatever.


00:50:32.000 --> 00:50:36.440
Yeah, so we have several layers of sandboxing.


00:50:36.440 --> 00:50:40.600
If it takes too long, or if it uses specific parts


00:50:40.600 --> 00:50:42.960
of the standard library that might be used in a malicious


00:50:42.960 --> 00:50:45.880
way, then it just doesn't do it at all.


00:50:45.880 --> 00:50:49.480
But even if it does do it, it's inside of one sandbox that's


00:50:49.480 --> 00:50:50.640
inside another sandbox.


00:50:50.640 --> 00:50:51.720
And it's very, very safe.


00:50:51.720 --> 00:50:52.800
And this is open source.


00:50:52.800 --> 00:50:55.320
You can take this tool, Snackbox,


00:50:55.320 --> 00:50:58.560
and you can use it in your bot, or in your website,


00:50:58.560 --> 00:51:00.120
or whatever service you want if you


00:51:00.120 --> 00:51:03.520
want to be able to safely evaluate Python code.


00:51:03.520 --> 00:51:04.080
Nice.


